\section{Beginning a run}

At the start of each program execution, [[begin_run]] stages all files
and creates (or amends) a commit with the run header.

The key decision is what to do when no files have changed since the last
run.
If the student runs the same program twice without editing anything,
we do not want a new empty commit---that would clutter the log with
duplicate snapshots.
Instead, we amend the previous commit to append a new run block.
This groups consecutive runs of identical code into a single commit,
which is what you want when reviewing the log.

When files \emph{have} changed, we create a fresh commit.
The diff in that commit shows exactly what the student modified between
runs.

<<repo methods>>=
def begin_run(self, script, args, start_time):
    """Record the start of a program run.

    Stages all files.  If there are changes, creates a new commit
    with the run header.  If no files changed, amends the previous
    commit to append a new run block.

    Returns the run header string (needed by :meth:`finalize_run`).
    """
    header = format_run_header(script, args, start_time)

    self.git("add", ".")
    diff = self.git("diff", "--cached", "--quiet")
    has_changes = diff.returncode != 0

    if has_changes:
        self.git("commit", "-m", header)
    else:
        <<amend previous commit with new run block>>

    return header
@

To amend, we read the existing commit message, add a separator, and
append the new run header.
On the very first run (the initial commit), this produces a commit
message with both the initial-commit line and the run header.

<<amend previous commit with new run block>>=
existing = self.git(
    "log", "-1", "--format=%B"
).stdout.rstrip("\n")
combined = existing + "\n\n---\n\n" + header
self.git(
    "commit", "--amend", "--allow-empty",
    "-m", combined,
)
@

Let's verify both the new-commit and amend paths:

<<test functions>>=
def test_begin_run_new_commit_on_file_change(workdir):
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    (workdir / "hello.py").write_text('print("changed")\n')
    now = datetime.datetime.now()
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], now)
    result = repo.git("log", "--oneline")
    lines = result.stdout.strip().split("\n")
    assert len(lines) == 2  # initial + run

def test_begin_run_amends_on_no_change(workdir):
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    now = datetime.datetime.now()
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], now)
    result = repo.git("log", "--oneline")
    lines = result.stdout.strip().split("\n")
    assert len(lines) == 1  # amended initial

def test_begin_run_two_runs_no_change_single_commit(workdir):
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    t1 = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 1, 10, 0)
    t2 = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 1, 10, 5)
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], t1)
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", ["--verbose"], t2)
    result = repo.git("log", "--oneline")
    lines = result.stdout.strip().split("\n")
    assert len(lines) == 1
    msg = repo.git("log", "-1", "--format=%B").stdout
    assert "---" in msg  # separator between runs

def test_begin_run_header_includes_args(workdir):
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    now = datetime.datetime.now()
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", ["arg1", "arg2"], now)
    msg = repo.git("log", "-1", "--format=%B").stdout
    assert "arg1 arg2" in msg

def test_begin_run_new_commit_after_edit(workdir):
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    t1 = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 1, 10, 0)
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], t1)
    (workdir / "hello.py").write_text('print("v2")\n')
    t2 = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 1, 10, 5)
    repo.begin_run("hello.py", [], t2)
    result = repo.git("log", "--oneline")
    lines = result.stdout.strip().split("\n")
    assert len(lines) == 2
